The paper deals with the complexity of solving clustering problems in Euclidean metrics, which is a topic that falls under the scope of several arXiv CS sub-categories. The focus on stable or perturbation-resilient instances suggests that the paper may be relevant to the sub-category of cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms), which deals with the design and analysis of algorithms for solving computational problems. The use of local search algorithms and the investigation of the complexity of solving clustering problems in fixed dimension Euclidean metrics suggest that the paper may also be relevant to the sub-category of cs.LG (Machine Learning), which deals with the development and analysis of algorithms for learning from data. The study of doubling metrics and the investigation of the complexity of solving stable clustering instances suggest that the paper may also be relevant to the sub-category of cs.CC (Computational Complexity), which deals with the study of the inherent difficulty of computational problems. The use of geometric techniques and the investigation of the complexity of solving clustering problems in Euclidean space suggest that the paper may also be relevant to the sub-category of cs.CG (Computational Geometry), which deals with the design and analysis of algorithms for solving geometric problems. Finally, the investigation of the complexity of solving stable clustering instances suggests that the paper may also be relevant to the sub-category of cs.IT (Information Theory), which deals with the study of the fundamental limits of information processing
